## 1. Core Mental Models

This file contains two distinct families of problems, both extremely high-frequency in placement interviews.

**Family 1 — Monotonic Data Structures (Sliding Window Max, Stock Span, Celebrity):**

The unifying idea: elements that can never be the answer to a future query should be eliminated immediately rather than stored. For sliding window maximum, a smaller element sitting behind a larger one in the window can never become the maximum for any future window — it is permanently useless and is discarded. For stock span, days already absorbed into a previous span computation never need to be revisited individually — their information is compressed into a single accumulated value. For the celebrity problem, a single comparison eliminates exactly one of two candidates.

A monotonic deque or stack acts as a curated candidate list: it stores only elements that have a chance of being the answer to a future query, in the order they would be queried. This curation converts an O(n times k) or O(n squared) brute force into O(n), because every element enters and leaves the structure at most once, amortized O(1) per element.

**Family 2 — Cache Design (LRU, LFU):**

The challenge is satisfying three simultaneous requirements: O(1) lookup by key, O(1) update of access order, and O(1) eviction of the least-useful item. No single data structure provides all three:

| Requirement | HashMap alone | Doubly Linked List alone |
|---|---|---|
| O(1) lookup by key | Yes | No (O(n) scan) |
| O(1) reorder given a pointer | No (no ordering) | Yes |
| O(1) remove least-useful item | No | Yes (tail removal) |

The resolution: pair a HashMap (key maps to node pointer) with a Doubly Linked List (nodes in recency or frequency order). The HashMap gives instant access to any node; the DLL lets you reorder or remove that node in O(1) using its pointers. This composition, using two simple structures whose strengths complement each other's weaknesses, is the canonical pattern for cache design, and LRU/LFU are the two most important examples in interview preparation.

