## 2. Sliding Window Maximum (LC 239)

**Problem:** Given array `nums` and integer `k`, return the maximum of every contiguous subarray of size k as the window slides left to right.

**Constraints:** `1 <= k <= n <= 100000`, `-10000 <= nums[i] <= 10000`.

**Example:**

```
nums = [1,3,-1,-3,5,3,6,7], k=3
Output: [3,3,5,5,6,7]
```

### Why Brute Force Fails

For each of the `n-k+1` window positions, scanning all k elements costs O(n times k). For n = k = 100000, that is 10 billion operations, far beyond a 1-second time limit. The inefficiency: consecutive windows share k-1 elements, but brute force recomputes from scratch every time, ignoring this overlap.

### Approach 1: Brute Force O(n times k)

```cpp
vector<int> maxSlidingWindow(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
    int n = nums.size();
    vector<int> result;
    for (int i = 0; i <= n - k; i++) {
        int maxVal = nums[i];
        for (int j = i + 1; j < i + k; j++) maxVal = max(maxVal, nums[j]);
        result.push_back(maxVal);
    }
    return result;
}
```

### Approach 2: Max-Heap O(n log k)

Maintain a max-heap of (value, index) pairs. The top is the current maximum candidate. Lazily discard stale entries (index out of window) when they surface at the top.

```cpp
vector<int> maxSlidingWindow(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
    priority_queue<pair<int,int>> pq;   // max-heap: {value, index}
    vector<int> result;
    for (int i = 0; i < (int)nums.size(); i++) {
        pq.push({nums[i], i});
        while (pq.top().second <= i - k) pq.pop();   // discard stale top
        if (i >= k - 1) result.push_back(pq.top().first);
    }
    return result;
}
```

Time: O(n log k). Space: O(n) worst case (stale entries linger until popped).

### Approach 3: Monotonic Deque O(n), Optimal

**Key insight:** Maintain a deque storing indices (never values) in decreasing order of their corresponding values. This gives two properties:

1. The front is always the index of the current window's maximum.
2. The back is always a valid future candidate.

**Two invariant-maintaining operations:**

- **Expire the front:** if the front index has slid out of the window (`front == i - k`), pop it.
- **Pop smaller elements from the back before inserting:** when inserting index `i`, any back element with value less than or equal to `nums[i]` can never be the maximum for any future window. `i` is to its right and at least as large, so `i` would always be chosen over it whenever both are in range. Discard permanently.

```cpp
vector<int> maxSlidingWindow(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
    deque<int> dq;   // stores indices; values strictly decreasing front-to-back
    vector<int> result;
    int n = nums.size();

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        // Expire front if it has left the window
        if (!dq.empty() && dq.front() == i - k) dq.pop_front();

        // Remove back elements that can never be useful again
        while (!dq.empty() && nums[dq.back()] <= nums[i]) dq.pop_back();

        dq.push_back(i);

        if (i >= k - 1) result.push_back(nums[dq.front()]);
    }
    return result;
}
```

**Why store indices, not values:** Checking expiry requires comparing positions, not magnitudes. If you stored values, you could not distinguish "this value has left the window" from "another instance of this same value is still inside." Always store indices; fetch values via `nums[dq.front()]`.

**Why each index is processed in amortized O(1):** Every index is pushed exactly once (one `push_back` per iteration) and popped at most once, either from the front (expiry) or from the back (displaced by a larger value). Total push plus pop operations across all n iterations is at most 2n. Hence O(n) total.

Time: O(n). Space: O(k).

### Dry Run: nums = [1,3,-1,-3,5,3,6,7], k=3

```
i=0: nums[0]=1. No expiry. No back pop. Push 0. dq=[0]. i<2, skip.
i=1: nums[1]=3. No expiry. Pop back: nums[0]=1<=3 -> pop 0. dq=[]. Push 1. dq=[1]. i<2, skip.
i=2: nums[2]=-1. No expiry. Pop back: nums[1]=3>-1 -> stop. Push 2. dq=[1,2]. i=2: result=[nums[1]]=[3].
i=3: nums[3]=-3. Expiry: dq.front()=1==3-3=0? No. Pop back: nums[2]=-1>-3 -> stop. Push 3. dq=[1,2,3]. result=[3,3].
i=4: nums[4]=5. Expiry: dq.front()=1==4-3=1? YES -> pop 1. dq=[2,3]. Pop back: nums[3]=-3<=5 -> pop 3. nums[2]=-1<=5 -> pop 2. dq=[]. Push 4. dq=[4]. result=[3,3,5].
i=5: nums[5]=3. Expiry: front=4==5-3=2? No. Pop back: nums[4]=5>3 -> stop. Push 5. dq=[4,5]. result=[3,3,5,5].
i=6: nums[6]=6. Expiry: front=4==6-3=3? No. Pop back: nums[5]=3<=6 -> pop 5. nums[4]=5<=6 -> pop 4. dq=[]. Push 6. dq=[6]. result=[3,3,5,5,6].
i=7: nums[7]=7. Expiry: front=6==7-3=4? No. Pop back: nums[6]=6<=7 -> pop 6. dq=[]. Push 7. dq=[7]. result=[3,3,5,5,6,7].

Final: [3,3,5,5,6,7]  (matches expected output)
```

### Edge Cases

| Input | k | Output | Reason |
|---|---|---|---|
| `[1]` | 1 | `[1]` | Single element, single window |
| `[1,2,3]` | 3 | `[3]` | Only one window total |
| `[3,2,1]` | 1 | `[3,2,1]` | Window size 1: every element is its own window |

