## 5. LRU Cache (LC 146)

**Problem:** Design a Least Recently Used cache with capacity `cap`. `get(key)` and `put(key, value)` must run in O(1). On eviction, remove the least recently used item. Both `get` and `put` count as a use, updating recency.

**Example:**

```
LRUCache(2)
put(1,1)        // {1=1}
put(2,2)        // {1=1, 2=2}
get(1) -> 1     // 1 becomes most recent: {2=2, 1=1}
put(3,3)        // evicts 2 (LRU): {1=1, 3=3}
get(2) -> -1    // evicted
```

### Why No Single Structure Suffices

See Section 1's table. The resolution: HashMap[key] equals node pointer; DLL holds nodes in recency order (most recently used at head, least recently used at tail).

### Design: Two Sentinel Nodes

Dummy `head` (MRU end) and dummy `tail` (LRU end) eliminate all null-pointer special cases when inserting or deleting at either end.

```
head <-> [most recent] <-> ... <-> [least recent] <-> tail
```

```cpp
class LRUCache {
    struct Node {
        int key, val;
        Node *prev, *next;
        Node(int k, int v) : key(k), val(v), prev(nullptr), next(nullptr) {}
    };

    int cap;
    unordered_map<int, Node*> mp;
    Node *head, *tail;

    void removeNode(Node* node) {
        node->prev->next = node->next;
        node->next->prev = node->prev;
    }

    void insertAfterHead(Node* node) {
        node->next = head->next;
        node->prev = head;
        head->next->prev = node;
        head->next = node;
    }

public:
    LRUCache(int capacity) : cap(capacity) {
        head = new Node(-1, -1);
        tail = new Node(-1, -1);
        head->next = tail;
        tail->prev = head;
    }

    int get(int key) {
        if (!mp.count(key)) return -1;
        Node* node = mp[key];
        removeNode(node);
        insertAfterHead(node);   // every access updates recency
        return node->val;
    }

    void put(int key, int value) {
        if (mp.count(key)) {
            mp[key]->val = value;
            removeNode(mp[key]);
            insertAfterHead(mp[key]);
        } else {
            if ((int)mp.size() == cap) {
                Node* lru = tail->prev;
                removeNode(lru);
                mp.erase(lru->key);
                delete lru;
            }
            Node* newNode = new Node(key, value);
            mp[key] = newNode;
            insertAfterHead(newNode);
        }
    }
};
```

**Pointer update checklist:**

`removeNode(node)` requires 2 updates:
- `node->prev->next = node->next`
- `node->next->prev = node->prev`

`insertAfterHead(node)` requires 4 updates:
- `node->next = head->next`
- `node->prev = head`
- `head->next->prev = node`
- `head->next = node`

Time: O(1) for both operations. Space: O(capacity).

### Dry Run: LRUCache(2)

```
put(1,1): head<->[1,1]<->tail. mp={1:n1}
put(2,2): head<->[2,2]<->[1,1]<->tail. mp={1:n1,2:n2}
get(1):   n1 removed, reinserted after head.
          head<->[1,1]<->[2,2]<->tail. return 1.
put(3,3): full. LRU=tail->prev=n2(key=2). Remove n2, erase mp[2].
          Insert [3,3] after head.
          head<->[3,3]<->[1,1]<->tail. mp={1:n1,3:n3}
get(2):   not in mp -> return -1
put(4,4): full. LRU=n1(key=1). Remove, erase mp[1].
          head<->[4,4]<->[3,3]<->tail. mp={3:n3,4:n4}
get(1):   -1 (evicted)
get(3):   move n3 to front. head<->[3,3]<->[4,4]<->tail. return 3
get(4):   move n4 to front. head<->[4,4]<->[3,3]<->tail. return 4
```

### Shorter Implementation with std::list

```cpp
class LRUCache {
    int cap;
    list<pair<int,int>> dll;                              // {key, value}, front = MRU
    unordered_map<int, list<pair<int,int>>::iterator> mp;

public:
    LRUCache(int capacity) : cap(capacity) {}

    int get(int key) {
        if (!mp.count(key)) return -1;
        dll.splice(dll.begin(), dll, mp[key]);   // move to front, O(1)
        return mp[key]->second;
    }

    void put(int key, int value) {
        if (mp.count(key)) {
            mp[key]->second = value;
            dll.splice(dll.begin(), dll, mp[key]);
        } else {
            if ((int)mp.size() == cap) {
                mp.erase(dll.back().first);
                dll.pop_back();
            }
            dll.push_front({key, value});
            mp[key] = dll.begin();
        }
    }
};
```

`list::splice` relocates a node in O(1) without invalidating iterators, a C++ standard guarantee that makes the stored iterators in `mp` remain valid after every splice.

