## 8. Unified Pattern Reference

### When to Use a Monotonic Deque

Appropriate when you need the maximum/minimum over a sliding fixed-size window, or when "useless" elements can be permanently discarded the moment a better candidate appears from the right.

| Signal | Use |
|---|---|
| Maximum/minimum in every window of size k | Decreasing/increasing monotonic deque |
| Next greater/smaller element | Monotonic stack |
| Span of consecutive smaller/equal elements | Monotonic stack with accumulated span |
| Previous greater element | Monotonic stack (scan left to right, compare against top) |

### When to Use a Monotonic Stack

Stock Span is the canonical template: while the stack is non-empty and the top is less than or equal to current, absorb its value and pop. The defining feature: popped elements' accumulated information is folded into the new top, never discarded outright.

### Cache Design Selection

| Cache type | Eviction policy | Structures | minFreq needed? |
|---|---|---|---|
| LRU | Least recently used | 1 HashMap + 1 DLL | No |
| LFU | Least frequently used, LRU tiebreak | 1 keyMap + 1 freqMap (multiple DLLs) | Yes |
| MRU | Most recently used | Same as LRU, evict from head instead of tail | No |

### Celebrity-Style Elimination Template

Any problem where a single comparison eliminates exactly one of two candidates:

1. Reduce n candidates to 1 using n-1 comparisons.
2. Verify the surviving candidate separately. Elimination alone never proves correctness.

