## 10. Common Mistakes and Pitfalls

### Mistake 1: Sliding Window Max, storing values instead of indices

```cpp
// WRONG: cannot reliably detect expiry; duplicate values cause ambiguity
deque<int> dq;   // stores VALUES
if (!dq.empty() && dq.front() == nums[i-k]) dq.pop_front();
// nums[i-k] might match a different, still-valid element elsewhere in the window!

// CORRECT: store indices; compare positions directly
deque<int> dq;   // stores INDICES
if (!dq.empty() && dq.front() == i - k) dq.pop_front();
```

### Mistake 2: Sliding Window Max, wrong expiry comparison

```cpp
// WRONG: using < instead of == lets expired elements linger one extra iteration
if (!dq.empty() && dq.front() < i - k) dq.pop_front();

// CORRECT: the window is [i-k+1, i]; index i-k has JUST left
if (!dq.empty() && dq.front() == i - k) dq.pop_front();
```

### Mistake 3: LRU Cache, forgetting to update recency on get

```cpp
// WRONG: get() returns the value but never marks the node as recently used
int get(int key) {
    if (!mp.count(key)) return -1;
    return mp[key]->val;   // missing: move to head
}

// CORRECT: every access, get or put, updates recency
int get(int key) {
    if (!mp.count(key)) return -1;
    removeNode(mp[key]);
    insertAfterHead(mp[key]);
    return mp[key]->val;
}
```

### Mistake 4: LRU Cache, not erasing the evicted key from the HashMap

```cpp
// WRONG: DLL node removed but stale key remains in the map (memory leak, wrong lookups)
Node* lru = tail->prev;
removeNode(lru);
// missing: mp.erase(lru->key);

// CORRECT: always update both structures together
Node* lru = tail->prev;
removeNode(lru);
mp.erase(lru->key);
delete lru;
```

### Mistake 5: LFU Cache, not resetting minFreq to 1 on new key insertion

```cpp
// WRONG: minFreq stays at its old (higher) value after a new freq-1 node is added
freqMap[1]->addFirst(newNode);
// If minFreq was 3, eviction will look in freqMap[3] instead of freqMap[1], which is wrong

// CORRECT: new nodes always start at freq=1, so minFreq must reset
minFreq = 1;
freqMap[1]->addFirst(newNode);
```

### Mistake 6: LFU Cache, not incrementing minFreq when its DLL empties

```cpp
// WRONG: after promoting the sole freq-1 node to freq-2, minFreq remains stuck at 1
// even though freqMap[1] is now empty
freqMap[f]->remove(node);
node->freq++;
// missing: if (freqMap[f]->size == 0 && f == minFreq) minFreq++;

// CORRECT: check before incrementing the node's frequency
freqMap[f]->remove(node);
if (freqMap[f]->size == 0 && f == minFreq) minFreq++;
node->freq++;
```

### Mistake 7: Celebrity Problem, skipping verification

```cpp
// WRONG: returns the survivor without checking it actually satisfies both conditions
return candidate;

// CORRECT: elimination only narrows to ONE POSSIBLE celebrity; verify before returning
for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    if (i == candidate) continue;
    if (!knows(i, candidate) || knows(candidate, i)) return -1;
}
return candidate;
```

### Mistake 8: Word Break, initializing dp[0] = false

```cpp
// WRONG: empty prefix base case missing, so no segmentation can ever be found
vector<bool> dp(n + 1, false);
// dp[0] never set to true

// CORRECT: empty string requires zero words, which is trivially valid
dp[0] = true;
```

### Mistake 9: Stock Span, forgetting to push the current price after popping

```cpp
// WRONG: forgets to push the current (price, span) onto the stack
while (!st.empty() && st.top().first <= price) { span += st.top().second; st.pop(); }
return span;   // missing st.push({price, span})

// CORRECT: always push after the absorbing loop, so future prices can absorb this one
while (!st.empty() && st.top().first <= price) { span += st.top().second; st.pop(); }
st.push({price, span});
return span;
```

